Sometimes both article and genitive are omitted, as in iv. 8 καθαρίσατε χεῖρας ἁμαρτωλοὶ καὶ ἁγνίσατε καρδίας δίψυχοι ‘cleanse your hands ye sinuers, and purify your hearts ye double- minded.' Probably this is to be explained as a proverbial phrase approaching to a compound, like our ‘shake-hands,' ‘up-stans) We may compare Sir. xxxviii. 10 εὔθυνον χεῖρας καὶ ἀπὸ πάσης ἁμαρτίας καθάρισον καρδίαν, 1 Maec. xii. :39 ἐζήτησε Τρύφων ἐκτεῖναι χεῖρα ἐπὶ Ἀντίοχον.

I will now take in order, with one or two exceptions Which will be noted later, the remaining instances in which an anarthrous Greek noun takes the definite article in the RV.
